search:Security Best Practices for NestJ.content:
- Use `nest new project-name` to create a new NestJS project.
- Install necessary packages using npm or yarn, e.g., `npm install @nestjs/microservices`.
- Configure gRPC microservice in `app.module.ts`:
  ```typescript
  import { Module } from '@nestjs/common';
  import { ClientsModule, Transport } from '@nestjs/microservices';

  @Module({
    imports: [
      ClientsModule.register([
        {
          name: 'GRPC_SERVICE',
          transport: Transport.GRPC,
          options: {
            url: 'localhost:50051',
            package: 'package_name',
            protoPath: join(__dirname, '..', 'path/to/your/proto/file.proto'),
          },
        },
      ]),
    ],
  })
  export class AppModule {}
  ```
- Use `@MessagePattern` decorator to define gRPC service methods in your controller.
- Ensure secure communication by using TLS with the `grpc.credentials.createSsl()` method when setting up the client options.
- Implement error handling within your service methods to manage exceptions properly.
- Deploy your NestJS microservice on Azure Kubernetes Service (AKS) using a LoadBalancer service type to expose it publicly.
